identification.name: identification
identification.description: The identification package describes a model of references and identifiers for information entities.

ARCHETYPE_ID.name: ARCHETYPE_ID
ARCHETYPE_ID.description:
Identifier for archetypes. Ideally these would identify globally unique archetypes.

Lexical form: `rm_originator  '-' rm_name  '-' rm_entity  '.' concept_name {  '-' specialisation }*  '.v' number`.

qualified_rm_entity.name: qualified_rm_entity
qualified_rm_entity.description: Globally qualified reference model entity, e.g.  `openehr-EHR-OBSERVATION`.

domain_concept.name: domain_concept
domain_concept.description: Name of the concept represented by this archetype, including specialisation, e.g. `Biochemistry_result-cholesterol`.

rm_originator.name: rm_originator
rm_originator.description: Organisation originating the reference model on which this archetype is based, e.g. openehr,  cen,  hl7 .

rm_name.name: rm_name
rm_name.description: Name of the reference model, e.g. rim,  ehr_rm,  en13606 .

rm_entity.name: rm_entity
rm_entity.description: Name of the ontological level within the reference model to which this archetype is targeted, e.g. for openEHR,  folder ,  composition ,  section ,  entry .

specialisation.name: specialisation
specialisation.description: Name of specialisation of concept, if this archetype is a specialisation of another archetype, e.g.  cholesterol .

GENERIC_ID.name: GENERIC_ID
GENERIC_ID.description: Generic identifier type for identifiers whose format is otherwise unknown to openEHR. Includes an attribute for naming the identification scheme (which may well be local).

scheme.name: scheme
scheme.description: Name of the scheme to which this identifier conforms. Ideally this name will be recognisable globally but realistically it may be a local ad hoc scheme whose name is not controlled or standardised in any way.

HIER_OBJECT_ID.name: HIER_OBJECT_ID
HIER_OBJECT_ID.description: Concrete type corresponding to hierarchical identifiers of the form defined by `UID_BASED_ID`.

LOCATABLE_REF.name: LOCATABLE_REF
LOCATABLE_REF.description: Purpose Reference to a `LOCATABLE` instance inside the top-level content structure inside a `VERSION<T>`; the path attribute is applied to the object that `VERSION._data_` points to.

path.name: path
path.description: The path to an instance in question, as an absolute path with respect to the object found at `VERSION._data_`. An empty path means that the object referred to by id being specified.

id.name: id
id.description: Globally unique id of an object, regardless of where it is stored.

as_uri.name: as_uri
as_uri.description:
A URI form of the reference, created by concatenating the following: 

* scheme, e.g. `ehr:`, derived from `_namespace_`
* `_id.value_`
* `/` + `_path_`, where `_path_` is non-empty

OBJECT_ID.name: OBJECT_ID
OBJECT_ID.description:
Ancestor class of identifiers of informational objects. Ids may be completely meaningless, in which case their only job is to refer to something, or may carry some information to do with the identified object. 

Object ids are used inside an object to identify that object. To identify another object in another service, use an `OBJECT_REF`, or else use a UID for local objects identified by UID. If none of the subtypes is suitable, direct instances of this class may be used.

value.name: value
value.description: The value of the id in the form defined below.

OBJECT_REF.name: OBJECT_REF
OBJECT_REF.description: Class describing a reference to another object, which may exist locally or be maintained outside the current namespace, e.g. in another service. Services are usually external, e.g. available in a LAN (including on the same host) or the internet via Corba, SOAP, or some other distributed protocol. However, in small systems they may be part of the same executable as the data containing the Id.

namespace.name: namespace
namespace.description:
Namespace to which this identifier belongs in the local system context (and possibly in any other openEHR compliant environment) e.g.  terminology ,  demographic . These names are not yet standardised. Legal values for `_namespace_` are:

* `"local"`
* `"unknown"`
* a string matching the standard regex `[a-zA-Z][a-zA-Z0-9_.:\/&?=+-]*`.

Note that the first two are just special values of the regex, and will be matched by it.

type.name: type
type.description: Name of the  class (concrete or abstract) of object to which this identifier type refers, e.g. `PARTY`, `PERSON`,  `GUIDELINE`  etc. These class names are from the relevant reference model. The type name `ANY` can be used to indicate that any type is accepted (e.g. if the type is unknown).

id.name: id
id.description: Globally unique id of an object, regardless of where it is stored.

OBJECT_VERSION_ID.name: OBJECT_VERSION_ID
OBJECT_VERSION_ID.description: Globally unique identifier for one version of a versioned object; lexical form: `object_id  '::' creating_system_id  '::' version_tree_id`.

object_id.name: object_id
object_id.description: Unique identifier for logical object of which this identifier identifies one version; normally the `_object_id_` will be the unique identifier of the version container containing the version referred to by this `OBJECT_VERSION_ID` instance.

creating_system_id.name: creating_system_id
creating_system_id.description: Identifier of the system that created the Version corresponding to this Object version id.

version_tree_id.name: version_tree_id
version_tree_id.description: Tree identifier of this version with respect to other versions in the same version tree, as either 1 or 3 part dot-separated numbers, e.g.  1 ,  2.1.4 .

is_branch.name: is_branch
is_branch.description: True if this version identifier represents a branch.

PARTY_REF.name: PARTY_REF
PARTY_REF.description: Identifier for parties in a demographic or identity service. There are typically a number of subtypes of the `PARTY` class, including `PERSON`, `ORGANISATION`, etc. Abstract supertypes are allowed if the referenced object is of a type not known by the current implementation of this class (in other words, if the demographic model is changed by the addition of a new `PARTY` or `ACTOR` subtypes, valid `PARTY_REFs` can still be constructed to them).

Type_validity.name: Type_validity
Type_validity.rule: type.is_equal(“PERSON”) or type.is_equal(“ORGANISATION”) or type.is_equal(“GROUP”) or type.is_equal(“AGENT”)or type.is_equal(“ROLE”) or type.is_equal(“PARTY”) or type.is_equal(“ACTOR”)

TERMINOLOGY_ID.name: TERMINOLOGY_ID
TERMINOLOGY_ID.description:
Identifier for terminologies such as accessed via a terminology query service. In this class, the value attribute identifies the Terminology in the terminology service, e.g.  SNOMED-CT . A terminology is assumed to be in a particular language, which must be explicitly specified.

The value if the id attribute is the precise terminology id identifier, including actual release (i.e. actual  version), local modifications etc; e.g. ICPC2.

Lexical form: `name [  '(' version  ')' ]`.

name.name: name
name.description: Return the terminology id (which includes the  version  in some cases). Distinct names correspond to distinct (i.e. non-compatible) terminologies. Thus the names  ICD10AM  and  ICD10  refer to distinct terminologies.

version_id.name: version_id
version_id.description: Version of this terminology, if versioning supported, else the empty string.

VERSION_TREE_ID.name: VERSION_TREE_ID
VERSION_TREE_ID.description:
Version tree identifier for one version. Lexical form: 

`trunk_version [  '.' branch_number  '.' branch_version ]`

trunk_version.name: trunk_version
trunk_version.description: Trunk version number; numbering starts at 1.

is_branch.name: is_branch
is_branch.description: True if this version identifier represents a branch, i.e. has branch_number and branch_version parts.

branch_number.name: branch_number
branch_number.description: Number of branch from the trunk point; numbering starts at 1.

branch_version.name: branch_version
branch_version.description: Version of the branch; numbering starts at 1.

Trunk_version_valid.name: Trunk_version_valid
Trunk_version_valid.rule: trunk_version /= Void and then trunk_version.is_integer and then trunk_version.as_integer >= 1

Branch_number_valid.name: Branch_number_valid
Branch_number_valid.rule: branch_number /= Void implies branch_number.is_integer and then branch_number.as_integer >= 1

Branch_version_valid.name: Branch_version_valid
Branch_version_valid.rule: branch_version /= Void implies branch_version.is_integer and then branch_version.as_integer >= 1

Branch_validity.name: Branch_validity
Branch_validity.rule: (branch_number = Void and branch_version = Void ) xor (branch_number /= Void and branch_version /= Void )

UID_BASED_ID.name: UID_BASED_ID
UID_BASED_ID.description: Abstract model of UID-based identifiers consisting of a root part and an optional extension; lexical form: `root '::' extension`.

root.name: root
root.description: The identifier of the conceptual namespace in which the object exists, within the identification scheme. Returns the part to the left of the first '::' separator, if any, or else the whole string.

extension.name: extension
extension.description: Optional local identifier of the object within the context of the root identifier. Returns the part to the right of the first '::' separator if any, or else any empty String.

UUID.name: UUID
UUID.description: Model of the DCE Universal Unique Identifier or UUID which takes the form of hexadecimal integers separated by hyphens, following the pattern 8-4-4-4-12 as defined by the Open Group, CDE 1.1 Remote Procedure Call specification, Appendix A. Also known as a GUID.

INTERNET_ID.name: INTERNET_ID
INTERNET_ID.description: Model of a reverse internet domain, as used to uniquely identify an internet domain. In the form of a dot-separated string in the reverse order of a domain name, specified by https://www.rfc-editor.org/info/rfc1034[IETF RFC 1034^].

UID.name: UID
UID.description: Abstract parent of classes representing unique identifiers which identify information entities in a durable way. UIDs only ever identify one IE in time or space and are never re-used.

ISO_OID.name: ISO_OID
ISO_OID.description: Model of ISO's Object Identifier (oid) as defined by the standard ISO/IEC 8824. Oids are formed from integers separated by dots. Each non-leaf node in an Oid starting from the left corresponds to an assigning authority, and identifies that authority's namespace, inside which the remaining part of the identifier is locally unique.

TEMPLATE_ID.name: TEMPLATE_ID
TEMPLATE_ID.description: Identifier for templates. Lexical form to be determined.

ACCESS_GROUP_REF.name: ACCESS_GROUP_REF
ACCESS_GROUP_REF.description: Reference to access group in an access control service.

definitions.name: definitions
definitions.description: The rm.support.definition package defines symbolic definitions used by the openEHR models. Only a small number are currently defined.

OPENEHR_DEFINITIONS.name: OPENEHR_DEFINITIONS
OPENEHR_DEFINITIONS.description: Inheritance class to provide access to constants defined in other packages.

Local_terminology_id.name: Local_terminology_id
Local_terminology_id.description: Predefined terminology identifier to indicate it is local to the knowledge resource in which it occurs, e.g. an archetype

VALIDITY_KIND.name: VALIDITY_KIND
VALIDITY_KIND.description:
An enumeration of three values that may commonly occur in constraint models.

Use as the type of any attribute within this model, which expresses constraint on some attribute in a class in a reference model. For example to indicate validity
of Date/Time fields.

VERSION_STATUS.name: VERSION_STATUS
VERSION_STATUS.description: Status of a versioned artefact, as one of a number of possible values: uncontrolled, prerelease, release, build.

Env.name: Env
Env.description: Class representing the real-world environment, providing basic information like current time, date, etc.

current_date.name: current_date
current_date.description: Return today's date in the current locale.

current_time.name: current_time
current_time.description: Return current time in the current locale.

current_date_time.name: current_date_time
current_date_time.description: Return current date/time in the current locale.

current_time_zone.name: current_time_zone
current_time_zone.description: Return the timezone of the current locale.

Statistical_evaluator.name: Statistical_evaluator
Statistical_evaluator.description: A basic statistical evaluator class providing common functions on collections of numbers.

sum.name: sum
sum.description: Sum of a container of values.

mean.name: mean
mean.description: Mean (arithmetic average) of a container of values.

median.name: median
median.description: Return numerically centre value in ordered form of container contents.

mode.name: mode
mode.description: Mode (most frequent) of a container of values.

max.name: max
max.description: Maximum of a container of values.

min.name: min
min.description: Minimum of a container of values.

count.name: count
count.description: Return the number of items in `_vals_`, i.e. `_vals.count_`.

std_dev.name: std_dev
std_dev.description: Compute standard deviation of a container of values.

primary_language.name: primary_language
primary_language.description: Primary language of the current locale.

convert_value.name: convert_value
convert_value.description: Convert `_value_` of physical property type (e.g. 'pressure' etc) from one units to another.

Hash.name: Hash
Hash.description: Type representing a keyed table of values. V is the value type, and K the type of the keys.

Hash<String, Hash<String, String>>.name: Hash<String, Hash<String, String>>
Hash<String, Hash<String, String>>.description: Two-level hash map structure, typically used for two levels of keyed tables, e.g. with outer keys = language ("en", "zh" etc) and inner keys = some tag or id or path.

Container.name: Container
Container.description: Abstract ancestor of container types whose items are addressable in some way.

has.name: has
has.description: Test for membership of a value.

there_exists.name: there_exists
there_exists.description: Existential quantifier applied to container, taking one agent argument `_test_` whose signature is `(v:T): Boolean`.

for_all.name: for_all
for_all.description: Universal quantifier applied to container, taking one agent argument `_test_` whose signature is `(v:T): Boolean`.

matching.name: matching
matching.description: Return a List all items matching the predicate function `_test_` which has signature `(v:T): Boolean`. If no matches, an empty List is returned.

select.name: select
select.description: Return first item matching the predicate function `_test_` which has signature `(v:T): Boolean`, or Void if no match.

List.name: List
List.description: Ordered container that may contain duplicates.

Set.name: Set
Set.description: Unordered container that may not contain duplicates.

Array.name: Array
Array.description: Container whose storage is assumed to be contiguous.

primitive_types.name: primitive_types
primitive_types.description: Some primitive/built-in types for the openEHR Reference Model.

Uri.name: Uri
Uri.description: A kind of String constrained to obey the syntax of RFC 3986.

Ordered_Numeric.name: Ordered_Numeric
Ordered_Numeric.description: Abstract notional parent class of ordered, numeric types, which are types with both the `_less_than_()` and arithmetic functions defined.

Integer.name: Integer
Integer.description: Type representing minimal interface of built-in Integer type.

less_than.name: less_than
less_than.description: Returns True if current Integer is less than `_other_`.

negative.name: negative
negative.description: Generate negative of current Integer value.

is_equal.name: is_equal
is_equal.description: Value equality: return True if `this` and `_other_` are attached to objects considered to be equal in value.

equal.name: equal
equal.description: Reference equality for reference types, value equality for value types.

Double.name: Double
Double.description: Type used to represent double-precision decimal numbers. Corresponds to a double-precision floating point value in most languages.

floor.name: floor
floor.description: Return the greatest integer no greater than the value of this object.

less_than.name: less_than
less_than.description: Returns True if current Double is less than `_other_`.

negative.name: negative
negative.description: Generate negative of current Double value.

is_equal.name: is_equal
is_equal.description: Value equality: return True if `this` and `_other_` are attached to objects considered to be equal in value.

equal.name: equal
equal.description: Reference equality for reference types, value equality for value types.

Numeric.name: Numeric
Numeric.description: Abstract parent class of numeric types, which are types which have various arithmetic and comparison operators defined.

add.name: add
add.description: Sum with `_other_` (commutative). Actual type of result depends on arithmetic balancing rules.

subtract.name: subtract
subtract.description: Result of subtracting `_other_`. Actual type of result depends on arithmetic balancing rules.

multiply.name: multiply
multiply.description: Product by `_other_`. Actual type of result depends on arithmetic balancing rules.

divide.name: divide
divide.description: Divide by`_other_`. Actual type of result depends on arithmetic balancing rules.

Octet.name: Octet
Octet.description: Type representing minimal interface of built-in Octet type.

Character.name: Character
Character.description: Type representing minimal interface of built-in Character type.

Boolean.name: Boolean
Boolean.description: Type representing minimal interface of built-in Boolean type.

negation.name: negation
negation.description: Boolean negation of the current value.

String.name: String
String.description: Type representing minimal interface of built-in String type, as used to represent textual data in any natural or formal language.

is_empty.name: is_empty
is_empty.description: True if string is empty, i.e. equal to "".

is_integer.name: is_integer
is_integer.description: True if string can be parsed as an integer.

as_integer.name: as_integer
as_integer.description: Return the integer corresponding to the integer value represented in this string.

append.name: append
append.description: Concatenation operator - causes `_other_` to be appended to this string.

less_than.name: less_than
less_than.description: Lexical comparison of string content based on ordering in relevant character set.

contains.name: contains
contains.description: Return True if this String contains `_other_` (case-sensitive).

Real.name: Real
Real.description: Type used to represent decimal numbers. Corresponds to a single-precision floating point value in most languages.

floor.name: floor
floor.description: Return the greatest integer no greater than the value of this object.

less_than.name: less_than
less_than.description: Returns True if current Real is less than `_other_`.

negative.name: negative
negative.description: Generate negative of current Real value.

is_equal.name: is_equal
is_equal.description: Value equality: return True if `this` and `_other_` are attached to objects considered to be equal in value.

equal.name: equal
equal.description: Reference equality for reference types, value equality for value types.

Integer64.name: Integer64
Integer64.description: Type representing minimal interface of built-in Integer64 type.

less_than.name: less_than
less_than.description: Returns True if current Integer is less than `_other_`.

negative.name: negative
negative.description: Generate negative of current Integer value.

is_equal.name: is_equal
is_equal.description: Value equality: return True if `this` and `_other_` are attached to objects considered to be equal in value.

equal.name: equal
equal.description: Reference equality for reference types, value equality for value types.

Ordered.name: Ordered
Ordered.description: Abstract parent class of ordered types i.e. types on which the '<' operator is defined.

less_than.name: less_than
less_than.description:
Arithmetic value comparison. Returns True if current object is less than `_other_`. This operator is effected and/or redefined in descendants to provide the appropriate ordering semantics for concrete types.

In conjunction with `=`, enables the definition of the related functions `_greater_than_()` etc.

less_than_or_equal.name: less_than_or_equal
less_than_or_equal.description: True if current object less than or equal to `_other_`.

greater_than.name: greater_than
greater_than.description: True if current object greater than `_other_`.

greater_than_or_equal.name: greater_than_or_equal
greater_than_or_equal.description: True if current object greater than or equal to `_other_`.

TUPLE.name: TUPLE
TUPLE.description: Parent type of all TUPLE types.

FUNCTION.name: FUNCTION
FUNCTION.description: Type representing a function with a return type and 0 or more arguments represented as a TUPLE.

TUPLE1.name: TUPLE1
TUPLE1.description: A Tuple type used, among other things, for representing a single typed argument within a Routine signature.

TUPLE2.name: TUPLE2
TUPLE2.description: A Tuple type used, among other things, for representing two typed arguments within a Routine signature.

ROUTINE.name: ROUTINE
ROUTINE.description: Type representing a function with a return type and 0 or more arguments represented as a TUPLE.

PROCEDURE.name: PROCEDURE
PROCEDURE.description: Type representing a procedure with 0 or more arguments represented as a TUPLE.

Iso8601_date_time.name: Iso8601_date_time
Iso8601_date_time.description:
Represents an ISO 8601 date/time, including partial and extended forms. Value may be:

* `YYYY-MM-DDThh:mm:ss[(,|.)sss][Z | ±hh[:mm]]` (extended, preferred) or
* `YYYYMMDDThhmmss[(,|.)sss][Z | ±hh[mm]]` (compact)
* or a partial variant.

See `_valid_iso8601_date_time()_` for validity.

Note that this class includes 2 deviations from ISO 8601:2004:

* for partial date/times, any part of the date/time up to the month may be missing, not just seconds and minutes as in the standard;
* the time `24:00:00` is not allowed, since it would mean the date was really on the next day.

year.name: year
year.description: Extract the year part of the date as an Integer.

month.name: month
month.description: Extract the month part of the date/time as an Integer, or return 0 if not present.

day.name: day
day.description: Extract the day part of the date/time as an Integer, or return 0 if not present.

hour.name: hour
hour.description: Extract the hour part of the date/time as an Integer, or return 0 if not present.

minute.name: minute
minute.description: Extract the minute part of the date/time as an Integer, or return 0 if not present.

second.name: second
second.description: Extract the integral seconds part of the date/time (i.e. prior to any decimal sign) as an Integer, or return 0 if not present.

fractional_second.name: fractional_second
fractional_second.description: Extract the fractional seconds part of the date/time (i.e. following to any decimal sign) as a Real, or return 0.0 if not present.

month_unknown.name: month_unknown
month_unknown.description: Indicates whether month in year is unknown.

day_unknown.name: day_unknown
day_unknown.description: Indicates whether day in month is unknown.

minute_unknown.name: minute_unknown
minute_unknown.description: Indicates whether minute in hour is known.

second_unknown.name: second_unknown
second_unknown.description: Indicates whether minute in hour is known.

is_decimal_sign_comma.name: is_decimal_sign_comma
is_decimal_sign_comma.description: True if this time has a decimal part indicated by `','` (comma) rather than `'.'` (period).

is_partial.name: is_partial
is_partial.description: True if this date time is partial, i.e. if seconds or more is missing.

is_extended.name: is_extended
is_extended.description: True if this date/time uses `'-'`, `':'` separators.

has_fractional_second.name: has_fractional_second
has_fractional_second.description: True if the `_fractional_second_` part is significant (i.e. even if = 0.0).

as_string.name: as_string
as_string.description: Return the string value in extended format.

add.name: add
add.description: Arithmetic addition of a duration to a date/time.

subtract.name: subtract
subtract.description: Arithmetic subtraction of a duration from a date/time.

add_nominal.name: add_nominal
add_nominal.description: Addition of nominal duration represented by `_a_diff_`. See `Iso8601_date._add_nominal_()` for semantics.

subtract_nominal.name: subtract_nominal
subtract_nominal.description: Subtraction of nominal duration represented by `_a_diff_`. See `_add_nominal_()` for semantics.

Iso8601_duration.name: Iso8601_duration
Iso8601_duration.description:
Represents an ISO 8601 duration, which may have multiple parts from years down to seconds. The `_value_` attribute is a String in the format:

* `P[nnY][nnM][nnW][nnD][T[nnH][nnM][nnS]]`

NOTE: two deviations from ISO 8601 are supported, the first, to allow a negative sign, and the second allowing the 'W' designator to be mixed with other designators.

years.name: years
years.description: Number of years in the `_value_`, i.e. the number preceding the `'Y'` in the `'YMD'` part, if one exists.

months.name: months
months.description: Number of months in the `_value_`, i.e. the value preceding the `'M'` in the `'YMD'` part, if one exists.

days.name: days
days.description: Number of days in the `_value_`, i.e. the number preceding the `'D'` in the `'YMD'` part, if one exists.

hours.name: hours
hours.description: Number of hours in the `_value_`, i.e. the number preceding the `'H'` in the `'HMS'` part, if one exists.

minutes.name: minutes
minutes.description: Number of minutes in the `_value_`, i.e. the number preceding the `'M'` in the `'HMS'` part, if one exists.

seconds.name: seconds
seconds.description: Number of seconds in the `_value_`, i.e. the integer number preceding the `'S'` in the `'HMS'` part, if one exists.

fractional_seconds.name: fractional_seconds
fractional_seconds.description: Fractional seconds in the `_value_`, i.e. the decimal part of the number preceding the `'S'` in the `'HMS'` part, if one exists.

weeks.name: weeks
weeks.description: Number of weeks in the `_value_`, i.e. the value preceding the `W`, if one exists.

is_decimal_sign_comma.name: is_decimal_sign_comma
is_decimal_sign_comma.description: True if this time has a decimal part indicated by ',' (comma) rather than '.' (period).

to_seconds.name: to_seconds
to_seconds.description: Total number of seconds equivalent (including fractional) of entire duration. Where non-definite elements such as year and month (i.e. 'Y' and 'M') are included, the corresponding 'average' durations from `Time_definitions` are used to compute the result.

add.name: add
add.description: Arithmetic addition of a duration to a duration, via conversion to seconds, using `Time_definitions._Average_days_in_year_` and `Time_definitions._Average_days_in_month_`

subtract.name: subtract
subtract.description: Arithmetic subtraction of a duration from a duration, via conversion to seconds, using `Time_definitions._Average_days_in_year_` and `Time_definitions._Average_days_in_month_`

multiply.name: multiply
multiply.description: Arithmetic multiplication a duration by a number.

divide.name: divide
divide.description: Arithmetic division of a duration by a number.

negative.name: negative
negative.description: Generate negative of current duration value.

Iso8601_time.name: Iso8601_time
Iso8601_time.description:
Represents an ISO 8601 time, including partial and extended forms. Value may be:

* `hh:mm:ss[(,|.)sss][Z|±hh[:mm]]` (extended, preferred) or
* `hhmmss[(,|.)sss][Z|±hh[mm]]` (compact)
* or a partial invariant.

See `_valid_iso8601_time()_` for validity.

NOTE: A small deviation to the ISO 8601:2004 standard in this class is that the time `24:00:00` is not allowed, for consistency with `Iso8601_date_time`.

hour.name: hour
hour.description: Extract the hour part of the date/time as an Integer.

minute.name: minute
minute.description: Extract the minute part of the time as an Integer, or return 0 if not present.

second.name: second
second.description: Extract the integral seconds part of the time (i.e. prior to any decimal sign) as an Integer, or return 0 if not present.

fractional_second.name: fractional_second
fractional_second.description: Extract the fractional seconds part of the time (i.e. following to any decimal sign) as a Real, or return 0.0 if not present.

minute_unknown.name: minute_unknown
minute_unknown.description: Indicates whether minute is unknown. If so, the time is of the form “hh”.

second_unknown.name: second_unknown
second_unknown.description: Indicates whether second is unknown. If so and month is known, the time is of the form `"hh:mm"` or `"hhmm"`.

is_decimal_sign_comma.name: is_decimal_sign_comma
is_decimal_sign_comma.description: True if this time has a decimal part indicated by `','` (comma) rather than `'.'` (period).

is_partial.name: is_partial
is_partial.description: True if this time is partial, i.e. if seconds or more is missing.

is_extended.name: is_extended
is_extended.description: True if this time uses `'-'`, `':'` separators.

has_fractional_second.name: has_fractional_second
has_fractional_second.description: True if the `_fractional_second_` part is significant (i.e. even if = 0.0).

as_string.name: as_string
as_string.description: Return string value in extended format.

add.name: add
add.description: Arithmetic addition of a duration to a time.

subtract.name: subtract
subtract.description: Arithmetic subtraction of a duration from a time.

Iso8601_timezone.name: Iso8601_timezone
Iso8601_timezone.description:
ISO8601 timezone string, in format:

* `Z | ±hh[mm]`

where:

* `hh` is "00" - "23" (0-filled to two digits)
* `mm` is "00" - "59" (0-filled to two digits)
* `Z` is a literal meaning UTC (modern replacement for GMT), i.e. timezone `+0000`

hour.name: hour
hour.description: Extract the hour part of timezone, as an Integer in the range `00 - 14`.

minute.name: minute
minute.description: Extract the hour part of timezone, as an Integer, usually either 0 or 30.

sign.name: sign
sign.description: Direction of timezone expresssed as +1 or -1.

is_partial.name: is_partial
is_partial.description: True if this time zone is partial, i.e. if minutes is missing.

is_extended.name: is_extended
is_extended.description: True if this time-zone uses ‘:’ separators.

is_gmt.name: is_gmt
is_gmt.description: True if timezone is UTC, i.e. `+0000`.

as_string.name: as_string
as_string.description: Return timezone string in extended format.

Min_hour_valid.name: Min_hour_valid
Min_hour_valid.rule: sign = -1 implies hour > 0 and hour <= Min_timezone_hour

Max_hour_valid.name: Max_hour_valid
Max_hour_valid.rule: sign = 1 implies hour > 0 and hour <= Max_timezone_hour

Iso8601_type.name: Iso8601_type
Iso8601_type.description: Abstract ancestor type of ISO 8601 types, defining interface for 'extended' and 'partial' concepts from ISO 8601.

value.name: value
value.description: Representation of all descendants is a single String.

is_partial.name: is_partial
is_partial.description: True if this date time is partial, i.e. if trailing end (right hand) value(s) is/are missing.

is_extended.name: is_extended
is_extended.description: True if this ISO8601 string is in the 'extended' form, i.e. uses `'-'` and / or `':'` separators. This is the preferred format.

Iso8601_date.name: Iso8601_date
Iso8601_date.description:
Represents an ISO 8601 date, including partial and extended forms. Value may be:

* `YYYY-MM-DD` (extended, preferred)
* `YYYYMMDD` (compact)
* a partial invariant.

See `Time_definitions._valid_iso8601_date()_` for validity.

year.name: year
year.description: Extract the year part of the date as an Integer.

month.name: month
month.description: Extract the month part of the date as an Integer, or return 0 if not present.

day.name: day
day.description: Extract the day part of the date as an Integer, or return 0 if not present.

month_unknown.name: month_unknown
month_unknown.description: Indicates whether month in year is unknown. If so, the date is of the form `"YYYY"`.

day_unknown.name: day_unknown
day_unknown.description: Indicates whether day in month is unknown. If so, and month is known, the date is of the form `"YYYY-MM"` or `"YYYYMM"`.

is_partial.name: is_partial
is_partial.description: True if this date is partial, i.e. if days or more is missing.

is_extended.name: is_extended
is_extended.description: True if this date uses `'-'` separators.

as_string.name: as_string
as_string.description: Return string value in extended format.

add.name: add
add.description: Arithmetic addition of a duration to a date.

subtract.name: subtract
subtract.description: Arithmetic subtraction of a duration from a date.

add_nominal.name: add_nominal

subtract_nominal.name: subtract_nominal
subtract_nominal.description: Subtraction of nominal duration represented by `_a_diff_`. See `_add_nominal_()` for semantics.

Day_valid.name: Day_valid
Day_valid.rule: not day_unknown implies valid_day (year, month, day)

Time_Definitions.name: Time_Definitions
Time_Definitions.description: Definitions for date/time classes. Note that the timezone limits are set by where the international dateline is. Thus, time in New Zealand is quoted using `+12:00`, not `-12:00`.

Seconds_in_minute.name: Seconds_in_minute
Seconds_in_minute.description: Number of seconds in a minute.

Minutes_in_hour.name: Minutes_in_hour
Minutes_in_hour.description: Number of minutes in an hour.

Hours_in_day.name: Hours_in_day
Hours_in_day.description: Number of clock hours in a day, i.e. 24.

Average_days_in_month.name: Average_days_in_month
Average_days_in_month.description: Used for conversions of durations containing months to days and / or seconds.

Max_days_in_month.name: Max_days_in_month
Max_days_in_month.description: Maximum number of days in any month.

Days_in_year.name: Days_in_year
Days_in_year.description: Calendar days in a normal year, i.e. 365.

Average_days_in_year.name: Average_days_in_year
Average_days_in_year.description: Used for conversions of durations containing years to days and / or seconds.

Days_in_leap_year.name: Days_in_leap_year
Days_in_leap_year.description: Calendar days in a standard leap year, i.e. 366.

Max_days_in_year.name: Max_days_in_year
Max_days_in_year.description: Maximum number of days in a year, i.e. accounting for leap years.

Days_in_week.name: Days_in_week
Days_in_week.description: Number of days in a week.

Months_in_year.name: Months_in_year
Months_in_year.description: Number of months in a year.

Min_timezone_hour.name: Min_timezone_hour
Min_timezone_hour.description: Minimum hour value of a timezone  according to ISO 8601 (note that the -ve sign is supplied in the `ISO8601_TIMEZONE` class).

Max_timezone_hour.name: Max_timezone_hour
Max_timezone_hour.description: Maximum hour value of a timezone according to ISO 8601.

Nominal_days_in_month.name: Nominal_days_in_month
Nominal_days_in_month.description: Used for conversions of durations containing months to days and / or seconds.

Nominal_days_in_year.name: Nominal_days_in_year
Nominal_days_in_year.description: Used for conversions of durations containing years to days and / or seconds.

valid_day.name: valid_day
valid_day.description: True if `d >= 1 and d <= days_in_month (m, y)`.

valid_hour.name: valid_hour
valid_hour.description: True if `(h >= 0 and h < Hours_in_day) or (h = Hours_in_day and m = 0 and s = 0)` .

valid_iso8601_date.name: valid_iso8601_date
valid_iso8601_date.description:
String is a valid ISO 8601 date, i.e. takes the complete form:

* `YYYY-MM-DD` (extended, preferred) or one of the partial forms `YYYY-MM` or `YYYY`
* `YYYYMMDD` (compact) or a partial variant `YYYYMM`.

Where:

* `YYYY` is the string form of any positive number in the range `0000` - `9999` (zero-filled to four digits)
* `MM` is `01` - `12` (zero-filled to two digits)
* `DD` is `01` - `31` (zero-filled to two digits)

The combinations of `YYYY`, `MM`, `DD` numbers must be correct with respect to the Gregorian calendar.

valid_iso8601_time.name: valid_iso8601_time
valid_iso8601_time.description:
String is a valid ISO 8601 date, i.e. takes the form:

* `hh:mm:ss[(,|.)s+][Z|±hh[:mm]]` (extended)
* `hhmmss[(,|.)s+][Z|±hh[mm]]` (compact)
* or one of the partial forms:
** `hh:mm` (extended)
** `hhmm` or `hh` (compact)

with an additional optional timezone indicator of:

* `Z` or `±hh[:mm]` (extended)  `±hh[mm]` (compact)

Where:

* `hh` is "00" - "23" (0-filled to two digits)
* `mm` is "00" - "59" (0-filled to two digits)
* `ss` is "00" - "60" (0-filled to two digits)
* `[(,|.)s+]` is an optional string consisting of a comma or decimal point followed by numeric string of 1 or more digits, representing a fractional second
* `Z` is a literal meaning UTC (modern replacement for GMT), i.e. timezone `+0000`

valid_iso8601_date_time.name: valid_iso8601_date_time
valid_iso8601_date_time.description:
String is a valid ISO 8601 date-time, i.e. takes the form:

* `YYYY-MM-DDThh:mm:ss[(,|.)s+][Z|±hh[:mm]]` (extended)
* `YYYYMMDDThhmmss[(,|.)s+][Z|±hh[mm]]` (compact)
* or one of the partial forms:
** `YYYY-MM-DDThh:mm` or `YYYY-MM-DDThh` (extended)
** `YYYYMMDDThhmm` or `YYYYMMDDThh` (compact)

valid_iso8601_duration.name: valid_iso8601_duration
valid_iso8601_duration.description:
String is a valid ISO 8601 duration, i.e. takes the form:

* `P[nnY][nnM][nnW][nnD][T[nnH][nnM][nnS]]`

Where each nn represents a number of years, months, etc. `nnW` represents a number of 7-day weeks.

Note: allowing the `W` designator in the same expression as other designators is an exception to the published standard, but necessary in clinical information (typically for representing pregnancy duration).

Multiplicity_interval.name: Multiplicity_interval
Multiplicity_interval.description: An Interval of Integer, used to represent multiplicity, cardinality and optionality in models.

Multiplicity_range_marker.name: Multiplicity_range_marker
Multiplicity_range_marker.description: Marker to use in string form of interval between limits.

Multiplicity_unbounded_marker.name: Multiplicity_unbounded_marker
Multiplicity_unbounded_marker.description: Symbol to use to indicate upper limit unbounded.

is_open.name: is_open
is_open.description: True if this interval imposes no constraints, i.e. is set to `0..*`.

is_optional.name: is_optional
is_optional.description: True if this interval expresses optionality, i.e. `0..1`.

is_mandatory.name: is_mandatory
is_mandatory.description: True if this interval expresses mandation, i.e. `1..1`.

is_prohibited.name: is_prohibited
is_prohibited.description: True if this interval is set to `0..0`.

Proper_interval.name: Proper_interval
Proper_interval.description: Type representing a 'proper' Interval, i.e. any two-sided or one-sided interval.

Interval.name: Interval
Interval.description: Interval abstraction, featuring upper and lower limits that may be open or closed, included or not included.

lower_included.name: lower_included
lower_included.description: `lower` boundary value included in range if not `lower_unbounded`.

upper_included.name: upper_included
upper_included.description: `upper` boundary value included in range if not `upper_unbounded`.

has.name: has
has.description: True if the value `e` is properly contained in this Interval.

intersects.name: intersects
intersects.description: True if there is any overlap between intervals represented by Current and `_other_`. True if at least one limit of other is strictly inside the limits of this interval.

contains.name: contains
contains.description: True if current interval properly contains `_other_`? True if all points of `_other_` are inside the current interval.

is_equal.name: is_equal
is_equal.description: True if current object's interval is semantically same as `_other_`.

Limits_consistent.name: Limits_consistent
Limits_consistent.rule: (not upper_unbounded and not lower_unbounded) implies lower <= upper

Limits_comparable.name: Limits_comparable
Limits_comparable.rule: (not upper_unbounded and not lower_unbounded) implies lower.strictly_comparable_to (upper)

Point_interval.name: Point_interval
Point_interval.description: Type representing an Interval that happens to be a point value. Provides an efficient representation that is substitutable for `Interval<T>` where needed.

lower_included.name: lower_included
lower_included.description: Lower boundary value included in range if not `_lower_unbounded_`.

upper_included.name: upper_included
upper_included.description: Upper boundary value included in range if not `_upper_unbounded_`.

Cardinality.name: Cardinality
Cardinality.description: Express constraints on the cardinality of container objects which are the values of multiply-valued attributes, including uniqueness and ordering, providing the means to state that a container acts like a logical list, set or bag.

is_ordered.name: is_ordered
is_ordered.description: True if the members of the container attribute to which this cardinality refers are ordered.

is_unique.name: is_unique
is_unique.description: True if the members of the container attribute to which this cardinality refers are unique.

is_bag.name: is_bag
is_bag.description: True if the semantics of this cardinality represent a bag, i.e. unordered, non-unique membership.

is_list.name: is_list
is_list.description: True if the semantics of this cardinality represent a list, i.e. ordered, non-unique membership.

is_set.name: is_set
is_set.description: True if the semantics of this cardinality represent a set, i.e. unordered, unique membership.

Terminology_code.name: Terminology_code
Terminology_code.description: Primitive type representing a standalone reference to a terminology concept, in the form of a terminology identifier, optional version, and a code or code string from the terminology.

terminology_id.name: terminology_id
terminology_id.description: The archetype environment namespace identifier used to identify a terminology. Typically a value like `"snomed_ct"` that is mapped elsewhere to the full URI identifying the terminology.

terminology_version.name: terminology_version
terminology_version.description: Optional string value representing terminology version, typically a date or dotted numeric.

code_string.name: code_string
code_string.description: A terminology code or post-coordinated code expression, if supported by the terminology. The code may refer to a single term, a value set consisting of multiple terms, or some other entity representable within the terminology.

uri.name: uri
uri.description: The URI reference that may be used as a concrete key into a notional terminology service for queries that can obtain the term text, definition, and other associated elements.

Terminology_term.name: Terminology_term
Terminology_term.description: Leaf type representing a standalone term from a terminology, which consists of the term text and the code, i.e. a concept reference.

concept.name: concept
concept.description: Reference to the terminology concept formally representing this term.

Any.name: Any
Any.description: Abstract ancestor class for all other classes. Usually maps to a type like `Any` or `Object` in an object-oriented technology. Defined here to provide value and reference equality semantics.

is_equal.name: is_equal
is_equal.description: Value equality: return True if `this` and `_other_` are attached to objects considered to be equal in value.

equal.name: equal
equal.description: Reference equality for reference types, value equality for value types.

instance_of.name: instance_of
instance_of.description: Create new instance of a type.

type_of.name: type_of
type_of.description: Type name of an object as a string. May include generic parameters, as in `"Interval<Time>"`.

not_equal.name: not_equal
not_equal.description: True if current object not equal to `_other_`. Returns not `_equal_()`.

resource.name: resource
resource.description: The rm.common.resource package defines the structure and semantics of the general notion of an online resource which has been created by a human author, and consequently for which natural language is a factor.

AUTHORED_RESOURCE.name: AUTHORED_RESOURCE
AUTHORED_RESOURCE.description: Abstract idea of an online resource created by a human author.

uid.name: uid
uid.description: Unique identifier of the family of archetypes having the same interface identifier (same major version).

original_language.name: original_language
original_language.description: Language in which this resource was initially authored. Although there is no language primacy of resources overall, the language of original authoring is required to ensure natural language translations can preserve quality. Language is relevant in both the description and ontology sections.

description.name: description
description.description: Description and lifecycle information of the resource.

is_controlled.name: is_controlled
is_controlled.description: True if this resource is under any kind of change control (even file copying), in which case revision history is created.

annotations.name: annotations
annotations.description: Annotations on individual items within the resource, keyed by path. The inner table takes the form of a Hash table of String values keyed by String tags.

translations.name: translations
translations.description: List of details for each natural translation made of this resource, keyed by language code. For each translation listed here, there must be corresponding sections in all language-dependent parts of the resource. The `_original_language_` does not appear in this list.

current_revision.name: current_revision
current_revision.description: Most recent revision in revision_history if is_controlled else  (uncontrolled) .

languages_available.name: languages_available
languages_available.description: Total list of languages available in this resource, derived from original_language and translations.

Current_revision_valid.name: Current_revision_valid
Current_revision_valid.rule: (current_revision /= Void and not is_controlled) implies current_revision.is_equal ("(uncontrolled)")

Translations_valid.name: Translations_valid
Translations_valid.rule: translations /= Void implies (not translations.is_empty and not translations.has (orginal_language.code_string))

RESOURCE_DESCRIPTION.name: RESOURCE_DESCRIPTION
RESOURCE_DESCRIPTION.description: Defines the descriptive meta-data of a resource.

original_author.name: original_author
original_author.description: Original author of this resource, with all relevant details, including organisation.

original_namespace.name: original_namespace
original_namespace.description: Namespace of original author's organisation, in reverse internet form, if applicable.

original_publisher.name: original_publisher
original_publisher.description: Plain text name of organisation that originally published this artefact, if any.

other_contributors.name: other_contributors
other_contributors.description: Other contributors to the resource, each listed in "name <email>"  form.

lifecycle_state.name: lifecycle_state
lifecycle_state.description: Lifecycle state of the resource, typically including states such as: initial, in_development, in_review, published, superseded, obsolete.

custodian_namespace.name: custodian_namespace
custodian_namespace.description: Namespace in reverse internet id form, of current custodian organisation.

custodian_organisation.name: custodian_organisation
custodian_organisation.description: Plain text name of current custodian organisation.

copyright.name: copyright
copyright.description: Optional copyright statement for the resource as a knowledge resource.

licence.name: licence
licence.description: Licence of current artefact, in format "short licence name <URL of licence>", e.g. "Apache 2.0 License <http://www.apache.org/licenses/LICENSE-2.0.html>"

ip_acknowledgements.name: ip_acknowledgements
ip_acknowledgements.description:
List of acknowledgements of other IP directly referenced in this archetype, typically terminology codes, ontology ids etc. Recommended keys are the widely known name or namespace for the IP source, as shown in the following example:

----
ip_acknowledgements = <
    ["loinc"] = <"This content from LOINC® is copyright © 1995 Regenstrief Institute, Inc. and the LOINC Committee, and available at no cost under the license at http://loinc.org/terms-of-use">
    ["snomedct"] = <"Content from SNOMED CT® is copyright © 2007 IHTSDO <ihtsdo.org>">
>
----

references.name: references
references.description: List of references of material on which this artefact is based, as a keyed list of strings. The keys should be in a standard citation format.

resource_package_uri.name: resource_package_uri
resource_package_uri.description: URI of package to which this resource belongs.

conversion_details.name: conversion_details
conversion_details.description:
Details related to conversion process that generated this model from an original, if relevant, as a list of name/value pairs. Typical example with recommended tags:

----
conversion_details = <
    ["source_model"] = <"CEM model xyz <http://location.in.clinicalelementmodels.com>">
    ["tool"] = <"cem2adl v6.3.0">
    ["time"] = <"2014-11-03T09:05:00">
>
----

other_details.name: other_details
other_details.description: Additional non-language-sensitive resource meta-data, as a list of name/value pairs.

details.name: details
details.description: Details of all parts of resource description that are natural language-dependent, keyed by language code.

TRANSLATION_DETAILS.name: TRANSLATION_DETAILS
TRANSLATION_DETAILS.description: Class providing details of a natural language translation.

language.name: language
language.description: Language of the translation, coded using ISO 639-1 (2 character) language codes.

author.name: author
author.description: Primary translator name and other demographic details.

accreditation.name: accreditation
accreditation.description: Accreditation of primary translator or group, usually a national translator's registration or association membership id.

version_last_translated.name: version_last_translated
version_last_translated.description: Version of this resource last time it was translated into the language represented by this `TRANSLATION_DETAILS` object.

other_contributors.name: other_contributors
other_contributors.description: Additional contributors to this translation, each listed in the preferred format of the relevant organisation for the artefacts in question. A typical default is `"name <email>"` if nothing else is specified.

RESOURCE_DESCRIPTION_ITEM.name: RESOURCE_DESCRIPTION_ITEM
RESOURCE_DESCRIPTION_ITEM.description: Language-specific detail of resource description. When a resource is translated for use in another language environment, each `RESOURCE_DESCRIPTION_ITEM` needs to be copied and translated into the new language.

language.name: language
language.description: The localised language in which the items in this description item are written. Coded using ISO 639-1 (2 character) language codes.

keywords.name: keywords
keywords.description: Keywords which characterise this resource, used e.g. for indexing and searching.

use.name: use
use.description: Description of the uses of the resource, i.e. contexts in which it could be used.

misuse.name: misuse
misuse.description: Description of any misuses of the resource, i.e. contexts in which it should not be used.

original_resource_uri.name: original_resource_uri
original_resource_uri.description: URIs of original clinical document(s) or description of which resource is a formalisation, in the language of this description item; keyed by meaning.

other_details.name: other_details
other_details.description: Additional language-senstive resource metadata, as a list of name/value pairs.

RESOURCE_ANNOTATIONS.name: RESOURCE_ANNOTATIONS
RESOURCE_ANNOTATIONS.description:
Object representing annotations on an archetype. These can be of various forms, with a documentation form defined so far, which has a multi-level tabular structure [ [ [String value, String key], path key], language key]. Example instance, showing the documentation structure.

--------
    documentation = <
        ["en"] = <
           ["/data[id2]"] = <
               ["ui"] = <"passthrough">
           >
           ["/data[id2]/items[id3]"] = <
               ["design note"] = <"this is a design note on Statement">
               ["requirements note"] = <"this is a requirements note on Statement">
               ["medline ref"] = <"this is a medline ref on Statement">
           >
        >
    >
--------

Other sub-structures might have different keys, e.g.  based on programming languages, UI toolkits etc.

documentation.name: documentation
documentation.description: Documentary annotations in a multi-level keyed structure.

aom2.name: aom2
aom2.description: The openEHR aom package contains the models necessary to describe the semantics of archetypes and templates, and their use within openEHR. These include ADL, the Archetype Definition Language (expressed in the form of a syntax specification), and the archetype package, defining the object-oriented semantics of archetypes and templates.

ARCHETYPE.name: ARCHETYPE
ARCHETYPE.description:
The `ARCHETYPE` class defines the core formal model of the root object of any archetype or template. It includes only basic identification information, and otherwise provides the structural connections from the Archetype to its constituent parts, i.e. definition (a `C_COMPLEX_OBJECT`), terminology (`ARCHEYTPE_TERMINOLOGY`) and so on. 
It is the parent class of all concrete types of archetype.

parent_archetype_id.name: parent_archetype_id
parent_archetype_id.description: Archetype reference of the specialisation par-ent of this archetype, if applicable. May take the form of an archetype interface identifier, i.e. the identifier up to the major version only, or can be deeper.

is_differential.name: is_differential
is_differential.description: Flag indicating whether this archetype is differential or flat in its contents. Top-level source archetypes have this flag set to True.

definition.name: definition
definition.description: Root node of the definition of this archetype.

rules.name: rules
rules.description: Rules relating to this archetype. Statements are expressed in first order predicate logic, and usually refer to at least two attributes.

concept_code.name: concept_code
concept_code.description: The concept code of the root object of the archetype, also standing for the concept of the archetype as a whole.

physical_paths.name: physical_paths
physical_paths.description: Set of language-independent paths extracted from archetype. Paths obey Xpath-like syntax and are formed from alternations of `C_OBJECT._node_id_` and `C_ATTRIBUTE._rm_attribute_name_` values.

logical_paths.name: logical_paths
logical_paths.description: Set of language-dependent paths extracted from archetype. Paths obey the same syntax as physical_paths, but with node_ids replaced by their meanings from the terminology.

specialisation_depth.name: specialisation_depth
specialisation_depth.description: Specialisation depth of this archetype; larger than 0 if this archetype has a parent. Derived from terminology.specialisation_depth.

is_specialised.name: is_specialised
is_specialised.description: True if this archetype is a specialisation of another.

AUTHORED_ARCHETYPE.name: AUTHORED_ARCHETYPE
AUTHORED_ARCHETYPE.description: Root object of a standalone, authored archetype, including all meta-data, description, other identifiers and lifecycle.

adl_version.name: adl_version
adl_version.description: ADL version if archetype was read in from an ADL sharable archetype.

build_uid.name: build_uid
build_uid.description: Unique identifier of this archetype artefact instance. A new identifier is assigned every time the content is changed by a tool. Used by tools to distinguish different revisions and/or interim snapshots of the same artefact.

rm_release.name: rm_release
rm_release.description: Semver.org compatible release of the most recent reference model release on which the archetype in its current version is based. This does not imply conformance only to this release, since an archetype may be valid with respect to multiple releases of a reference model.

is_generated.name: is_generated
is_generated.description: If True, indicates that this artefact was machine-generated from some other source, in which case, tools would expect to overwrite this artefact on a new generation. Editing tools should set this value to False when a user starts to manually edit an archetype.

TEMPLATE.name: TEMPLATE
TEMPLATE.description: Class representing source template, i.e. a kind of archetype that may include template overlays, and may be restricted by tools to only defining mandations, prohibitions, and restrictions on elements already defined in the flat parent.

overlays.name: overlays
overlays.description: Overlay archetypes, i.e. partial archetypes that include full definition and terminology, but logically derive all their meta-data from from the owning template.

OPERATIONAL_TEMPLATE.name: OPERATIONAL_TEMPLATE
OPERATIONAL_TEMPLATE.description:
Root object of an operational template. An operational template is derived from a `TEMPLATE` definition and the `ARCHETYPEs` and/or `TEMPLATE_OVERLAYs` mentioned by that template by a process of flattening, and potentially removal of unneeded languages and terminologies.

An operational template is used for generating and validating RM-canonical instance data, and also as a source artefact for generating other downstream technical artefacts, including XML schemas, APIs and UI form definitions.

component_terminologies.name: component_terminologies
component_terminologies.description: Compendium of flattened terminologies of archetypes externally referenced from this archetype, keyed by archetype identifier. This will almost always be present in a template.

terminology_extracts.name: terminology_extracts
terminology_extracts.description: Directory of term definitions as a two-level  table. The outer hash keys are term codes,  e.g. "at4", and the inner hash key are term  attribute names, e.g. "text", "description" etc.

TEMPLATE_OVERLAY.name: TEMPLATE_OVERLAY
TEMPLATE_OVERLAY.description: A concrete form of the bare `ARCHETYPE` class, used to represent overlays in a source template. Overlays have no meta-data of their own, and are instead documented by their owning template.

ARCHETYPE_HRID.name: ARCHETYPE_HRID
ARCHETYPE_HRID.description: Human-readable structured identifier (HRID) for an archetype or template.

rm_publisher.name: rm_publisher
rm_publisher.description: Name of the Reference Model publisher.

rm_package.name: rm_package
rm_package.description: Name of the package in whose reachability graph the `_rm_class_` class is found (there can be more than one possibility in many reference models).

rm_class.name: rm_class
rm_class.description: Name of the root class of this archetype.

concept_id.name: concept_id
concept_id.description: The short concept name of the archetype as used in the multi-axial `_archetype_hrid_`.

release_version.name: release_version
release_version.description: The full numeric version of this archetype consisting of 3 parts, e.g. `"1.8.2"`. The `_archetype_hrid_` feature includes only the major version.

version_status.name: version_status
version_status.description:
The status of the version, i.e.:

* released: (empty string)
* release_candidate: `"rc"`
* alpha: `"alpha"`
* beta: `"beta"`

build_count.name: build_count
build_count.description: The build count since last increment of any version part.

semantic_id.name: semantic_id
semantic_id.description: The 'interface' form of the HRID, i.e. down to the major version.

physical_id.name: physical_id
physical_id.description: The 'physical' form of the HRID, i.e. with complete version information specified by `_version_id()_`.

version_id.name: version_id
version_id.description: Full version identifier string, based on `_release_version_`, `_version_status_`, and `_build_count_` e.g. `"1.8.2-rc.4"`.

major_version.name: major_version
major_version.description: Major version of this archetype, extracted from `_release_version_`.

minor_version.name: minor_version
minor_version.description: Minor version of this archetype, extracted from `_release_version_`.

patch_version.name: patch_version
patch_version.description: Patch version of this archetype, extracted from `_release_version_`. Equivalent to patch version in patch version in `semver.org` sytem.

constraint_model.name: constraint_model
constraint_model.description: The archetype Constraint Model is completely generic, and is designed to express the semantics of constraints on instances of classes which are themselves described in UML (or a similar object-oriented meta-model). Accordingly, the major abstractions in this model correspond to major abstractions in object-oriented formalisms, including several variations of the notion of  object' and the notion of  attribute'. The notion of  object' rather than  class' or  type' is used because archetypes are about constraints on data (i.e.  instances', or  objects') rather than models, which are constructed from  classes'.

ARCHETYPE_CONSTRAINT.name: ARCHETYPE_CONSTRAINT
ARCHETYPE_CONSTRAINT.description: Abstract parent of all constraint model types. Defines conformance and congruence function signatures.

parent.name: parent
parent.description: Parent node, except in the case of the top of a tree, i.e. root `C_COMPLEX_OBJECT` of an archetype definition.

is_prohibited.name: is_prohibited
is_prohibited.description: True if this node is prohibited. Implemented in subtypes.

has_path.name: has_path
has_path.description: True if the relative path a_path exists at this node.

path.name: path
path.description: Path of this node relative to root of archetype.

c_conforms_to.name: c_conforms_to
c_conforms_to.description:
True if constraints represented by this node, ignoring any sub-parts, are narrower or the same as other. 
Typically used during validation of special-ised archetype nodes.

c_congruent_to.name: c_congruent_to
c_congruent_to.description:
True if constraints represented by this node contain no further redefinitions with respect to the node other, with the exception of node_id redefnition in `C_OBJECT` nodes. 

Typically used to test if an inherited node locally contains any constraints.

is_second_order_constrained.name: is_second_order_constrained
is_second_order_constrained.description: True if there is a second order constraint such as a tuple constraint on this node.

is_root.name: is_root
is_root.description: True if this node is the root of the tree.

is_leaf.name: is_leaf
is_leaf.description: True if this node is a terminal node in the tree structure, i.e. having no child nodes.

Post.name: Post
Post.rule: Result = soc_parent /= Void or parent.soc_parent /= Void

C_OBJECT.name: C_OBJECT
C_OBJECT.description: Abstract model of constraint on any kind of object node.

rm_type_name.name: rm_type_name
rm_type_name.description: Reference model type that this node corresponds to.

occurrences.name: occurrences
occurrences.description:
Occurrences of this object node in the data, under the owning attribute. Upper limit can only be greater than 1 if owning attribute has a cardinality of more than 1.
Only set if it overrides the parent archetype in the case of specialised archetypes, or else the occurrences inferred from the underlying reference model existence and/or cardinality of the containing attribute.

node_id.name: node_id
node_id.description:
Semantic identifier of this node, used to distinguish sibling nodes. All nodes must have a `_node_id_`; for nodes under a container `C_ATTRIBUTE`, the id must be an id-code must be defined in the archetype terminology. For valid structures, all node ids are id-codes.

For `C_PRIMITIVE_OBJECTs` represented in ADL inline form, this attribute will have the special value `Primitive_node_id`; otherwise it will have the node id read during parsing.

is_deprecated.name: is_deprecated
is_deprecated.description: True if this node and by implication all sub-nodes are deprecated for use.

sibling_order.name: sibling_order
sibling_order.description: Optional indicator of order of this node with respect to another sibling. Only meaningful in a specialised archetype for a `C_OBJECT` within a `C_ATTRIBUTE` with `_is_multiple_` = True.

specialisation_depth.name: specialisation_depth
specialisation_depth.description: Level of specialisation of this archetype node, based on its node_id. The value 0 corresponds to non-specialised, 1 to first-level specialisation and so on. The level is the same as the number of ‘.’ characters in the node_id code. If node_id is not set, the return value is -1, signifying that the specialisation level should be determined from the nearest parent `C_OBJECT` node having a node_id.

c_conforms_to.name: c_conforms_to
c_conforms_to.description:
True if constraints represented by this node, ignoring any sub-parts, are narrower or the same as other. 
Typically used during validation of special-ised archetype nodes.

c_congruent_to.name: c_congruent_to
c_congruent_to.description:
True if constraints represented by this node contain no further redefinitions with respect to the node `_other_`, with the exception of node_id redefnition in `C_OBJECT` nodes. 

Typically used to test if an inherited node locally contains any constraints.

occurrences_conforms_to.name: occurrences_conforms_to
occurrences_conforms_to.description: True if this node `_occurrences_` conforms to `_other.occurrences_`; `other' is assumed to be in a flat archetype.

node_id_conforms_to.name: node_id_conforms_to
node_id_conforms_to.description: True if this node id conforms to other.node_id, which includes the ids being identical; other is assumed to be in a flat archetype.

is_prohibited.name: is_prohibited
is_prohibited.description: True if this `C_OBJECT` node is prohibited, i.e. if its occurrences is 0..0.

C_ATTRIBUTE.name: C_ATTRIBUTE
C_ATTRIBUTE.description: Abstract model of constraint on any kind of attribute in a class model.

rm_attribute_name.name: rm_attribute_name
rm_attribute_name.description: Reference model attribute within the enclosing type represented by a `C_OBJECT`.

existence.name: existence
existence.description: Constraint settable on every attribute, regardless of whether it is singular or of a container type, which indicates whether its target object exists or not (i.e. is mandatory or not). Only set if it overrides the underlying reference model or parent archetype in the case of specialised archetypes.

children.name: children
children.description: Child `C_OBJECT` nodes. Each such node represents a constraint on the type of this attribute in its reference model. Multiples occur both for multiple items in the case of container attributes, and alternatives in the case of singular attributes.

differential_path.name: differential_path
differential_path.description: Path to the parent object of this attribute (i.e. doesn’t include the name of this attribute). Used only for attributes in differential form, specialised archetypes. Enables only the re-defined parts of a specialised archetype to be expressed, at the path where they occur.

cardinality.name: cardinality
cardinality.description: Cardinality constraint of attribute, if a container attribute.

is_multiple.name: is_multiple
is_multiple.description: Flag indicating whether this attribute constraint is on a container (i.e. multiply-valued) attribute.

any_allowed.name: any_allowed
any_allowed.description: True if there is no effective constraint on the children of the RM attribute to which this `C_ATTRIBUTE` refers.

is_mandatory.name: is_mandatory
is_mandatory.description: True if this `C_ATTRIBUTE` has an existence constraint of 1..1, i..e. mandation.

rm_attribute_path.name: rm_attribute_path
rm_attribute_path.description: Path of this attribute with respect to owning `C_OBJECT`, including differential path where applicable.

is_single.name: is_single
is_single.description: True if this node logically represents a single-valued attribute. Evaluated as not is_multiple.

c_congruent_to.name: c_congruent_to
c_congruent_to.description:
True if constraints represented by this node contain no further redefinitions with respect to the node other, with the exception of node_id redefnition in `C_OBJECT` nodes. 

Typically used to test if an inherited node locally contains any constraints.

c_conforms_to.name: c_conforms_to
c_conforms_to.description:
True if constraints represented by this node, ignoring any sub-parts, are narrower or the same as other. 
Typically used during validation of special-ised archetype nodes.

is_prohibited.name: is_prohibited
is_prohibited.description: True if this `C_ATTRIBUTE` has an existence constraint of 0..0, i.e. prohibition.

C_DEFINED_OBJECT.name: C_DEFINED_OBJECT
C_DEFINED_OBJECT.description: Abstract parent type of `C_OBJECT` subtypes that are defined by value, i.e. whose definitions are actually in the archetype rather than being by reference.

default_value.name: default_value
default_value.description: Default value set in a template, and present in an operational template. Generally limited to leaf and near-leaf nodes.

any_allowed.name: any_allowed
any_allowed.description: True if any value (i.e. instance) of the reference model type would be allowed. Redefined in descendants.

valid_value.name: valid_value
valid_value.description: True if `_a_value_` is valid with respect to constraint expressed in concrete instance of this type.

prototype_value.name: prototype_value
prototype_value.description: Generate a prototype value from this constraint object.

has_default_value.name: has_default_value
has_default_value.description: True if there is an assumed value.

C_COMPLEX_OBJECT_PROXY.name: C_COMPLEX_OBJECT_PROXY
C_COMPLEX_OBJECT_PROXY.description: A constraint defined by proxy, using a reference to an object constraint defined elsewhere in the same archetype. Note that since this object refers to another node, there are two objects with available occurrences values. The local occurrences value on a `COMPLEX_OBJECT_PROXY` should always be used; when setting this from a serialised form, if no occurrences is mentioned, the target occurrences should be used (not the standard default of `{1..1}`); otherwise the locally specified occurrences should be used as normal. When serialising out, if the occurrences is the same as that of the target, it can be left out.

target_path.name: target_path
target_path.description: Reference to an object node using archetype path notation.

use_target_occurrences.name: use_target_occurrences
use_target_occurrences.description: True if target occurrences are to be used as the value of occurrences in this object; by the time of runtime use, the target occurrences value has to be set into this object.

occurrences_conforms_to.name: occurrences_conforms_to
occurrences_conforms_to.description:
True if this node occurrences conforms to `_other.occurrences_`; `_other_` is assumed to be in a flat archetype.

If `_other_` is a `C_COMPLEX_OBJECT`, then always `True`, since if occurrences defined on proxy node, it is an override of  the occurrences on the target, and it doesn't have to conform to anything except the containing attribute's cardinality. However, if `_other_` is also a `C_COMPLEX_OBJECT` then the override is of another use_node, and normal occurrences apply

ARCHETYPE_SLOT.name: ARCHETYPE_SLOT
ARCHETYPE_SLOT.description: Constraint describing a  slot' where another archetype can occur.

includes.name: includes
includes.description: List of constraints defining other archetypes that could be included at this point.

excludes.name: excludes
excludes.description: List of constraints defining other archetypes that cannot be included at this point.

is_closed.name: is_closed
is_closed.description: True if this slot specification in this artefact is closed to further filling either in further specialisations or at runtime. Default value False, i.e. unless explicitly set, a slot remains open.

any_allowed.name: any_allowed
any_allowed.description: True if no constraints stated, and slot is not closed.

C_PRIMITIVE_OBJECT.name: C_PRIMITIVE_OBJECT
C_PRIMITIVE_OBJECT.description: Parent of types representing constraints on primitive types.

assumed_value.name: assumed_value
assumed_value.description: Value to be assumed if none sent in data.

is_enumerated_type_constraint.name: is_enumerated_type_constraint
is_enumerated_type_constraint.description: True if this object represents a constraint on an enumerated type from the reference model, where the latter is assumed to be based on a primitive type, generally Integer or String.

constraint.name: constraint
constraint.description:
Constraint represented by this object; redefine in descendants.

Instances of this type represented in ADL inline form, the `_node_id_` attribute will have the special value `Primitive_node_id`; otherwise it will have the node id read during parsing.

has_assumed_value.name: has_assumed_value
has_assumed_value.description: True if there is an assumed value.

constrained_typename.name: constrained_typename
constrained_typename.description: Generate name of native type that is constrained by this `C_XXX` type. For most types, it is the `C_XXX` typename without the `C_`, i.e. `XXX`. E.g. `C_INTEGER` -> `Integer`. For the date/time types the mapping is different.

c_conforms_to.name: c_conforms_to
c_conforms_to.description:
True if constraints represented by this node, ignoring any sub-parts, are narrower or the same as other. 
Typically used during validation of special-ised archetype nodes.

c_value_conforms_to.name: c_value_conforms_to
c_value_conforms_to.description: True if this node expresses a value constraint that conforms to that of `other`. Effected in descendants.

c_congruent_to.name: c_congruent_to
c_congruent_to.description:
True if constraints represented by this node contain no further redefinitions with respect to the node `_other_`, with the exception of node_id redefnition in `C_OBJECT` nodes. 

Typically used to test if an inherited node locally contains any constraints.

c_value_congruent_to.name: c_value_congruent_to
c_value_congruent_to.description: True if this node expresses the same value constraint as `other`. Effected in descendants.

SIBLING_ORDER.name: SIBLING_ORDER
SIBLING_ORDER.description:
Defines the order indicator that can be used on a `C_OBJECT` within a container attribute in a specialised archetype to indicate its order with respect to a sibling defined in a higher specialisation level.

Misuse: This type cannot be used on a `C_OBJECT` other than one within a container attribute in a specialised archetype.

is_before.name: is_before
is_before.description: True if the order relationship is ‘before’, if False, it is ‘after’.

sibling_node_id.name: sibling_node_id
sibling_node_id.description: Node identifier of sibling before or after which this node should come.

is_after.name: is_after
is_after.description: True if the order relationship is `_after_`, computed as the negation of `_is_before_`.

C_ATTRIBUTE_TUPLE.name: C_ATTRIBUTE_TUPLE
C_ATTRIBUTE_TUPLE.description: Object representing a constraint on an atttribute tuple, i.e. a group of attributes that are constrained together. Typically used for representing co-varying constraints like {units, range} constraints.

members.name: members
members.description: List of `C_ATTRIBUTEs` forming the definition of the tuple.

c_conforms_to.name: c_conforms_to
c_conforms_to.description: True if constraints represented by this node, ignoring any sub-parts, are narrower or the same as other. Typically used during validation of specialised archetype nodes.

c_congruent_to.name: c_congruent_to
c_congruent_to.description: True if constraints represented by this node contain no further redefinitions with respect to the node other. Typically used to test if an inherited node locally contains any constraints.

C_PRIMITIVE_TUPLE.name: C_PRIMITIVE_TUPLE
C_PRIMITIVE_TUPLE.description: Class representing a single object tuple instance in a tuple constraint. Each such instance is a vector of object constraints, where each member (each `C_PRIMITIVE_OBJECT`) corresponds to one of the `C_ATTRIBUTEs` referred to by the owning `C_ATTRIBUTE_TUPLE`.

members.name: members
members.description: Object constraint members of this tuple group.

c_conforms_to.name: c_conforms_to
c_conforms_to.description: True if constraints represented by this node, ignoring any sub-parts, are narrower or the same as other. Typically used during validation of specialised archetype nodes.

c_congruent_to.name: c_congruent_to
c_congruent_to.description: True if constraints represented by this node contain no further redefinitions with respect to the node other. Typically used to test if an inherited node locally contains any constraints.

C_SECOND_ORDER.name: C_SECOND_ORDER
C_SECOND_ORDER.description: Abstract parent of classes defining second order constraints.

members.name: members
members.description: Members of this second order constrainer. Normally redefined in descendants.

c_conforms_to.name: c_conforms_to
c_conforms_to.description: True if constraints represented by this node, ignoring any sub-parts, are narrower or the same as other. Typically used during validation of specialised archetype nodes.

c_congruent_to.name: c_congruent_to
c_congruent_to.description: True if constraints represented by this node contain no further redefinitions with respect to the node other. Typically used to test if an inherited node locally contains any constraints.

C_ARCHETYPE_ROOT.name: C_ARCHETYPE_ROOT
C_ARCHETYPE_ROOT.description:
A specialisation of `C_COMPLEX_OBJECT` whose node_id attribute is an archetype identifier rather than the normal internal node code (i.e. id-code).

Used in two situations. The first is to represent an 'external reference' to an archetype from within another archetype or template. This supports re-use. The second use is within a template, where it is used as a slot-filler. 

For a new external reference, the `_node_id_` is set in the normal way, i.e. with a new code at the specialisation level of the archetype.

For a slot-filler or a redefined external reference, the `_node_id_` is set to a specialised version of the `_node_id_` of the node being specialised, allowing matching to occur during flattening.

In all uses within source archetypes and templates, the `_children_` attribute is `Void`.

In an operational template, the `_node_id_` is converted to the `_archetype_ref_`, and the structure contains the result of flattening any template overlay structure and the underlying flat archetype.

archetype_ref.name: archetype_ref
archetype_ref.description: Reference to archetype is being used to fill a slot or redefine an external reference. Typically an 'interface' archetype id, i.e. identifier with partial version information.

C_COMPLEX_OBJECT.name: C_COMPLEX_OBJECT
C_COMPLEX_OBJECT.description: Constraint on complex objects, i.e. any object that consists of other object constraints.

attributes.name: attributes
